Image Descriptors¶

Objectives:

  • Practising with different keypoint detectors and image descriptors
  • Applying image descriptors in image matching

Harris corner detector¶

In [3]:
local_region_size = 3 #size of local image regions W 
kernel_size = 3 #kernel size of Sobel kernels used for calculating derivatives I_x and I_y
k = 0.04 #parameter k 
threshold = 1000.0 #threshold theta
In [4]:
img_gray = np.float32(img_gray)
In [5]:
Harris_res_img = cv.cornerHarris(img_gray, local_region_size, kernel_size, k)

plt.figure(figsize= size)
plt.imshow(Harris_res_img, 'gray')
Out[5]:
<matplotlib.image.AxesImage at 0x1df7b20af60>
In [6]:
cv.imwrite('Harris_res_img.png', Harris_res_img)
Out[6]:
True

selecting and highlighting corners from Harris_res_img using our defined threshold¶

In [7]:
highlighted_colour = [0, 0, 255] # a colour is a combination of blue, green, red; red=[0,0,255]
highlighted_img = img.copy()
highlighted_img[Harris_res_img > threshold] = highlighted_colour
plt.figure(figsize= size)
plt.imshow(highlighted_img[:,:,::-1]) # RGB-> BGR as opencv only takes BGR

After applying and calculating the Harris corner detector with different thresholds, we found that the image calculated with greater value of threshold is less likely to get its corners detected using harris corner detector, image with less value of threshold is more likely to get its corners detected using harris corner detector. We found that in this case, the optimum value of threshold is 1000.¶

SIFT¶

Initialise SIFT detector¶

In [24]:
sift = cv.xfeatures2d.SIFT_create()

(A). Keypoint detection¶

Extracting keypoints (aka interest points)

In [25]:
# You need re-create img_gray as its previous version have been converted to float

img_gray = cv.cvtColor(img, cv.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)

kp = sift.detect(img_gray, None)

Visualising SIFT keypoints¶

In [26]:
img_gray_kp = img_gray.copy()
img_gray_kp = cv.drawKeypoints(img_gray, kp, img_gray_kp)

plt.figure(figsize= size)
plt.imshow(img_gray_kp)
print("Number of detected keypoints: %d" % (len(kp)))

(B). Descriptor computation¶

Based on the detected keypoints, we extract SIFT descriptors using the following commands¶

In [30]:
kp, des = sift.compute(img_gray, kp)
In [31]:
print(des.shape)

(2804, 128)

des is an array of size (2804x128). The rows correspond to keypoints and thus there are 2804 rows. The columns represent descriptors, each column store a descriptor including 128 elements.

In [32]:
img_45 = cv.imread('D:\Deakin University (Applied AI (Professional)\SIT789 (Applications of Computer Vision and Speech Processing)\Tasks & Assignments\Task-3.1P\Resources_3.1\empire_45.jpg')
img_zoomedout = cv.imread('D:\Deakin University (Applied AI (Professional)\SIT789 (Applications of Computer Vision and Speech Processing)\Tasks & Assignments\Task-3.1P\Resources_3.1\empire_zoomedout.jpg')
img_45_gray = cv.cvtColor(img_45, cv.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
img_zoomedout_gray = cv.cvtColor(img_zoomedout, cv.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
img_another = cv.imread('D:/Deakin University (Applied AI (Professional)/SIT789 (Applications of Computer Vision and Speech Processing)/Tasks & Assignments/Task-3.1P/Resources_3.1/fisherman.jpg')
img_another_gray = cv.cvtColor(img_another, cv.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)

Both keypoint detection and descriptor computation can be done silmutaneously by calling "sift.detectAndCompute"¶

In [33]:
kp_45, des_45 = sift.detectAndCompute(img_45_gray, None)
kp_zoomedout, des_zoomedout = sift.detectAndCompute(img_zoomedout_gray, None)
kp_another, des_another = sift.detectAndCompute(img_another_gray, None)
In [34]:
print("The number of keypoints in img_gray is %d" % (len(des)))
print("The number of keypoints in img_45_gray is %d" % (len(des_45)))

The number of keypoints in img_gray is 2804
The number of keypoints in img_45_gray is 3290

Computing the Hausdorff distances between: 1. des and des_45, 2. des and des_zoomedout & 3. des and des_another¶

In [35]:
from scipy.spatial.distance import directed_hausdorff
In [36]:
u = des
v = des_45
directed_hausdorff(u, v)[0]
Out[36]:
399.8762308514973
In [37]:
directed_hausdorff(v, u)[0]
Out[37]:
400.4697241989711

The general (symmetric) Hausdorff distance between two 2-D arrays of coordinates:

In [38]:
max(directed_hausdorff(u, v)[0], directed_hausdorff(v, u)[0])
Out[38]:
400.4697241989711

Indices of the points that generate the Hausdorff distance (the Hausdorff pair):

In [39]:
directed_hausdorff(v, u)[1:]
Out[39]:
(2685, 2732)

3. des and des_another¶

In [44]:

Out[44]:
433.89630097524457
In [45]:

Out[45]:
432.90645640831
In [46]:

Out[46]:
433.89630097524457
In [47]:
directed_hausdorff(b, a)[1:]
Out[47]:
(943, 2801)

Using the Hausdorff distances on images between descriptors: 'des and des_45', 'des and des_zoomedout', 'des and des_another'

  • We found that image 'empire' and 'empire_45' is very similar with hausdorff distance of 400.4697
  • While the hausdorff distance between 'des and des_zoomedout' is very similar to 'des and des_45' with a value of 401.3365
  • Even the image with totally different dimensions and pixels (des and des_another) have not that much greater hausdorff distance (value of 433.8963)
  • It shows that even though we can compare the distances of the image using hausdorff distance, we still can't rely on this method as this method is not very precise and the values are very similar to each other which makes the image similarity difficult to distinguish using hausdorff distance
